Introduction

During the Baroque era (1600-1750) the musical language of tonality became fully developed. In this lesson we will consider in greater detail intervals, triads, and chord progressions, exploring how these musical elements contributed to the development of tonality.

Later in the lesson we will listen to an early Baroque composition, examining various aspects of the music that contribute to the greatness of the work, while illustrating the concepts introduced in this lesson.

title: Intervals: Numeric Size
contents:
Simply put, an interval is the distance between two pitches.

From our examination of intervals so far, we know that the numeric size of an interval (that is, the number) is always determined by the letter names of the pitches. Let’s review this in a few different ways.

Recall the intervals in the C major scale, measuring from the tonic to the various scale degrees:

  • C to C (same pitch) is a unison (1st).
  • C to D is a 2nd.
  • C to E is a 3rd.
  • C to F is a 4th.
  • C to G is a 5th.
  • C to A is a 6th.
  • C to B is a 7th.
  • C to C is an octave (8th).

It doesn’t matter whether there are accidentals (such as sharps and flats) in front of the two notes: the numeric size of an interval is always determined by the letter names of the pitches. Granted, accidentals can change the quality of an interval, as we’ll see. And while it’s true that the actual size of an interval (in terms of half-steps) can be changed by accidentals, the number we use to name the interval does not change.

Intervals: 2nds

Take, for example, the interval of a 2nd. Any two adjacent letter-name pitches will be some kind of a 2nd. While we’ll concern ourselves with the qualities—the specific types—of 2nds on the next page of this lesson, we already know enough to recognize that there are different types of 2nds. And it’s true that the different qualities of 2nds are different sizes.

Think of the C major scale. Each pair of adjacent pitches creates the interval of a 2nd:

  • C to D is a 2nd.
  • D to E is a 2nd.
  • E to F is a 2nd.
  • F to G is a 2nd.
  • G to A is a 2nd.
  • A to B is a 2nd.
  • B to C is a 2nd.

We know, for example, that C to D is a whole step, while E to F is a half-step. Both intervals are 2nds, but they are different qualities, or types, of 2nds. When we examine the various qualities of intervals, we will learn how to specify the difference between the two.

Just to drive the point home: C-sharp to D-flat is a 2nd, even though the two pitches are enharmonically equivalent pitches. Why? Because . . .

The numeric size of an interval is always determined by the letter names of the pitches.

Intervals: Interval Quality

Let's consider now interval quality; that is, the various qualities of intervals.

“Apples and oranges.”

It’s an interesting fact of the way our definitions have evolved: Depending on the numeric size, an interval can have either the quality of “Perfect” or of “Major/minor.” For example, the interval of a 5th can be Perfect (P5), but it can never be Major or minor. On the other hand, the interval of a 3rd can be Major (M3) or minor (m3), but it can never be Perfect.

The Major scale.

The intervals of the major scale provide the standard for establishing the qualities of intervals. The intervals measured from the tonic to the various scale degrees will be either “Perfect” or “Major.”

Once again, consider the intervals in the C major scale, measuring from the tonic to the various scale degrees. We can now measure both the numeric size and the quality:

Perfect Major

C to C (same pitch) is a unison (1st). P1

C to D is a 2nd. M2

C to E is a 3rd. M3

C to F is a 4th. P4

C to G is a 5th. P5

C to A is a 6th. M6

C to B is a 7th. M7

C to C is an octave (8th). P8

Intervals: Larger or smaller.

For the unison (1st), 4th, 5th, and octave (8th), an interval one-half step larger than “Perfect” is “Augmented” (e.g., A5, or +5); an interval one-half step smaller than Perfect is “diminished” (e.g., d5, or °5). Let’s listen to the various qualities of 5th:

For the 2nd, 3rd, 6th, and 7th, an interval one-half step larger than “Major” is “Augmented” (e.g., A3, or +3); an interval one-half step smaller than “Major” is “minor” (e.g., m3); and an interval one-half step smaller than “minor” is “diminished” (e.g., d3, or °3). Let’s listen to the various qualities of 3rd:

So there are three qualities of 1st, 4th, 5th, and 8th intervals:

diminished, Perfect, Augmented.

There are four qualities of 2nd, 3rd, 6th, and 7th intervals:

diminished, minor, Major, Augmented.

These various interval qualities are important to the establishment of tonality, and Heading 4they help explain the differences between major and minor tonality. And they help us understand the different types of triads in our music.

Intervals: 2nds and 3rds

2nds and 3rds are really important. Scales are composed of successive 2nds. And our triads are composed of successive 3rds. You can determine the quality of a 2nd or 3rd (or of any interval, for that matter) by relating it to a Major scale, where all the intervals measured from tonic are either Perfect or Major.

With 2nds and 3rds, though, you can just as easily count the half steps. For example, C to D is a Major 2nd (M2), because by definition, a Major 2nd is the distance between tonic and the second scale degree in a major scale. So, then, C to D-flat is a minor 2nd (m2), because by definition, a minor interval is one-half step smaller than the corresponding Major interval.

We can also observe that a Major 2nd is a whole step, and minor 2nd is a half-step.

Similarly, we can observe that a Major 3rd (M3), such as C to E, is two whole steps, and a minor 3rd (m3), such as C to E-flat, is one-and-one-half steps.

Look at the keyboard:

  • C to D is a M2
  • D to E is a M2
  • E to F is a m2
  • F to G is a M2
  • G to A is a M2
  • A to B is a M2
  • B to C is a m2
  • C to E is a M3
  • D to F is a m3
  • E to G is a m3
  • F to A is a M3
  • G to B is a M3
  • A to C is a m3
  • B to D is a m3

Interval Inversions

6ths and 7ths are very difficult to count by half step. But every 6th is an "inversion" of a 3rd, and every 7th is an inversion of a 2nd.

Here's what that means:

C up to E is a 3rd; but if we turn the notes around by transposing the C up an octave, then E up to C is a 6th. We could figure that E to C is m6 by determining that the key of E major has 4 sharps (F#, C#, G#, D#); so then, E to C# is by definition a M6, which means that E to C is a m6.

Or we could recognize that Major intervals "invert" to minor. This means that, since C to E is a M3, then E to C is a m6. Reciprocally, minor intervals “invert” to Major. So, since C to E-flat is a m3, then E-flat to C is a M6.

By the same process, since C to D is a M2, then D to C is a m7. And since C to D-flat is a m2, then D-flat to C is a M7.

And so it goes . . .

Triads

Recall that triads are three-note chords built by stacking two intervals of a 3rd, one on top of the other. The three chord members are the root, third, and fifth. Triads are the fundamental harmony of tonality.

While there are four types of triads, we will concern ourselves with only three of them. And let’s start with the two most important: the major triad and the minor triad. The only difference between these two is the quality of the third. The root and the fifth are the same for both. (The interval between the root and fifth is a Perfect 5th in both the major triad and the minor triad.)

In the major triad, the interval between the root and the third is a Major 3rd (M3). In the minor triad, the interval between the root and the third is a minor 3rd (m3). For example: C – E – G is a major triad; C – E-flat – G is a minor triad.

The difference in the sound between a major triad and a minor triad is striking. The major triad tends to sound brighter, even happier. The minor triad tends to sound darker, more serious, even sad. These are important differences to perceive, because they get to the heart of the emotive power of our music.

Diatonic triads

Triads that are built from the notes of a diatonic scale are called diatonic triads. These are the ones you may have seen with Roman numerals, such as the diatonic triads of a major key. Let’s look, for example at the diatonic triads in C major:

I, ii, iii, IV, V, vi, vii°

Each of the scale degrees has a name. We already know that the first scale degree is “tonic,” and that the fifth scale degree is “dominant.” The name for the fourth scale degree is “subdominant.”

Notice that in a major key, the tonic (I), subdominant (IV), and dominant (V) triads are all major, signified by using capital Roman numerals. These three chords are sometimes referred to as the harmonic pillars of tonality. They are also the principle chords used in the blues and in rock-and-roll.

Notice, too, that the triads built on the second, third, and sixth scale degrees are minor, signified by the lower case Roman numerals. (The triad built on the seventh scale degree is something else, and we’ll get to that soon.)

Recall that we describe an interval or chord either as relatively stable and harmonious—a consonance—or as relatively unstable and harsh sounding—a dissonance. Technically speaking, the major and minor triads are the only chords that are considered consonant. In classical tonality, then, the tonic chord is either a major triad (“I,” in a major key) or a minor triad (“i,” in a minor key). These are the only chords stable enough to serve as tonic in the traditional language of tonality.

Inversions of triads

When we consider which intervals are consonant in our musical language, we can understand why the major and minor triads are regarded as consonant chords. In “root position”—that is, with the root of the triad in the bass—all the intervals contained in the triad are consonant: Between root and third is the interval of a 3rd; between third and fifth is the interval of a 3rd; and between root and fifth is the interval of a Perfect 5th. Each of these intervals is a consonance.

When we place the triad in “first inversion”—that is, with the third of the triad in the bass—remarkably, we still have all consonances, as measured from the bass. The fifth of the triad is the interval of a 3rd above the bass, and the root of the triad is the interval of a 6th above the bass. True, there is an interval of a Perfect 4th between the fifth of the triad and the root above it, but we do not interpret it as a dissonance, since it is not a 4th as measured from the bass.

We refer to triads in first inversion as “6-3 chords,” because those are the intervals in the chord, as measured from the bass. These “6-3 chords,” along with the root position major and minor triads, provide all the essential consonant harmonies in tonality.

We will consider the triad in “second inversion”—that is, with the fifth of the triad in the bass—a bit later. These “6-4 chords” are important. But it is a more complicated situation, because there is a dissonant Perfect 4th between the fifth of the triad in the bass and the root of the triad above it.

Chord progressions

In Renaissance music, such as the “Kyrie” we heard by Palestrina in the last lesson, multiple vocal lines are combined to create polyphony. The resulting harmonies often sound like major and minor triads—which they are. Interestingly, though, for Renaissance composers these were not chords, as we think of them; rather, they were intervals resulting from the interactions of melodic lines, combined in ways that allowed for the “proper” resolutions of dissonances into consonant sonorities.

As we observed, this is the art of counterpoint—of combining “note-against-note”—which creates the polyphonic textures that characterize much Renaissance music. And while we might sense an emerging “tonality” in the harmonies of late Renaissance polyphony, we tend to hear a succession of harmonies, more so than a purposeful progression.

In the Renaissance style we hear the marvelous sounds of diatonic major and minor triads, but they are still lacking the purposeful, directed motion that characterizes tonal chord progressions. This directed harmonic motion—toward either the tonic or dominant as a harmonic goal—was the invention of composers in the Baroque era. This is the essential, distinctive characteristic of tonality that distinguishes it from all other types of music.

In Lesson 2 we heard several examples of the chord progression: I - IV - V - I. In those examples, the tonic chord, I, was the harmonic goal of the progression, or phrase. This goal is most strongly realized by hearing the dominant chord, V, immediately before the tonic, creating the important concluding progression, V - I.

At its simplest—and as it was presented in the earlier lesson—the chord progression, I - IV - V - I, can be played as four chords in root position, and all voices moving in parallel motion:

This progression was presented this way for the sake of clarity, since it’s easier to see and recognize the notes of a triad when they are stacked one on top of another. As we might expect, though, this is not the way music tends to be composed.

Composers in the Baroque era—and those who followed in the Classical and Romantic eras—did not move all voices together in parallel motion. In fact, parallel 5ths and parallel octaves were against the “rules” of “voice-leading”—because they tended to undermine the independence of the individual voices. “Voice leading” is another term to describe the art of counterpoint.

Let’s look and listen to a more normal way of writing the progression, I - IV - V - I. Notice that the voice leading includes important moments of contrary motion between the bass line and the voices above it. Note, especially, the three voices above the bass, each descending melodically, as the bass steps up from IV to V.

Homophony

In the examples on the previous page, all four voices are moving from one chord to the next at the same time. That creates a different harmonic texture than the polyphonic textures we heard in Palestrina. It’s a texture known as homophony, and also referred to as “homo-rhythmic,” since each voice is adhering to the same rhythm. This is the sort of texture we might still encounter in many Protestant church hymnals. (And that points to an earlier rich history, which we will visit later in this unit.)

It’s worth noting that Renaissance composers also used homophonic textures—for contrast—in addition to the imitative polyphonic textures we heard in the Palestrina “Kyrie.” Still, the Renaissance style is notable for its overlapping, imitative entries of voices so often heard in the sacred music of the era.

Let’s consider some additional homophonic chord progressions that will introduce the use of “6-3 chords” in these progressions. This one, for example, uses the first inversion of the IV chord (“IV6”) in place of the root position IV chord. (Note: “6-3 chords” are abbreviated as “6” chords when using Roman numerals.)

And here’s the same chord progression in the parallel minor; that is, C minor:

Cadences

In these two previous examples, the tonic (I or i) is the harmonic goal of the four-bar phrase. When we reach a point of relative repose at the end of a phrase, that’s called a “cadence.” And when the cadence is a V - I progression, as it is in the previous examples, it’s called an “authentic cadence.”

The authentic cadence is the essential substance of tonal music. It is the affirmation of the tonic by means of directed harmonic motion.

But there is more. Not only does the dominant harmony (V) lead us inevitably to the tonic (I or i), dominant harmony itself serves as an important intermediate harmonic goal. Many phrases in tonal music reach a point of relative repose—which is to say, cadence—on dominant harmony (V). A phrase that concludes, or cadences, on the dominant chord (V) is known as a half cadence.

The half cadence is as essential to tonal music as the authentic cadence. Tonal music would not exist without these two cadences. The authentic cadence and the half cadence are the bread and butter of tonality.

Let’s modify our previous four-bar example in C minor, so that we reach relative repose on the dominant harmony. One way we can do this is by inserting a passing “6-3 chord” between the I chord and the iv6. This creates a stepwise descent in the bass from the tonic pitch to the dominant (i.e., C, B-flat, A-flat, G). Listen to the way this phrase concludes on the dominant chord in bar four. This is a half cadence.

The Baroque Style

The stylistic era of the Baroque began as a reaction against the restrained yet complex, "classical" sound of Renaissance polyphony. In the 1590s a group of artists and intellectuals in Florence, known as the Florentine Camerata, sought to revive the glories of ancient Greek music drama and, in the process, invented opera. The great Italian composer Claudio Monteverdi brought opera to life in 1607 with L'Orfeo. For the next 300 years, opera was in many respects "the best show in town."

One of the important textural changes in the Baroque style was to move away from the essential equality among multiple voices exhibited in the Renaissance style of imitative polyphony, and to place the emphasis on the outer voices. A single melodic line on top, and its relationship to a prominent bass line: these were the voices that mattered most. (btw, we use the term “voice” to refer to any line of music, whether vocal or instrumental.) There were still inner voices to fill the harmonic texture, but they were not emphasized, and their role became subordinate and supportive.

Let's turn briefly to England, to get a sense of the power of this Baroque style in seventeenth-century opera, as well as to appreciate the language of tonality, which by the late 1600s was the musical language of all of Western Europe. England's greatest composer at that time was Henry Purcell. His most well known work is the opera, Dido and Aeneas (1689). And the most famous aria, or song, from the opera is "Dido's Lament," which the queen sings when she is left desolate and heart-broken by her lover Aeneas, who must sail away to fulfill his destiny of founding Rome.

(Dido & Aeneas, Chandos Records, Ltd., 1981)

Basso Ostinato

"Dido's Lament" is built over a recurring bass line—what is referred to as a basso ostinato, or a "stubborn" bass. This bass line repeats for a total of eleven statements, running through the entirety of the aria. Remarkably, the bass line is woven into the fabric of the piece so artfully that it’s easy to miss the repetition on first listening. During the Baroque era, quite a few pieces were written over a basso ostinato.

The bass line of “Dido’s Lament” is notable for its chromatic descent from tonic to dominant. A chromatic descent is one that moves downward by successive half-steps, or semitones. So, for example, in the key of G minor, the chromatic descent would start on the tonic G, and descend to F-sharp, then to F, to E, to E-flat, and then reach the dominant D.

This basso ostinato highlights relationship between the tonic and the dominant, which is the defining characteristic of tonality. Before Dido begins to sing, we hear the bass line by itself. Notice how compelling the descent from tonic to dominant is, and then how the bass line moves inevitably from the dominant pitch back to the tonic.

Chromatic Elaboration

Let’s listen once again to the diatonic progression: i - v6 - iv6 - V. This time, we’ll transpose the phrase from C minor to G minor:

Now let’s compare that progression with the opening measures of the song:

Notice that the fundamental diatonic progression, i - v6 - iv6 - V, is still in place, but that Purcell has elaborated and enriched the progression by “filling in” all the half-steps along the bass’s descent from tonic to dominant.

Such use of chromaticism—while it emerged in the late Renaissance—was a harbinger of a new stylistic era, one that was expanding the harmonic vocabulary, infusing the music with more dissonances, even as all these elements were being drawn together to affirm fundamental underlying structures of tonal music.

Musical Meaning

"Dido's Lament" is in a minor key, which is a mode that listeners universally identify with sadness and seriousness. The musical meaning of the language of tonality begins, then, with our distinctly different responses to the major and minor keys. This aria, performed here by Emma Kirkby, is regarded by many as one of the most profoundly sad and beautiful in all of Western art music.

A notable melodic motive in the aria is the two-note falling semitone, which we first hear on the word "laid" in the opening line, "When I am laid . . ." This motive is often referred to as a "sighing" motive--for good reason. Notice in the instrumental coda (“tail,” in Italian), after Dido has finished singing, how prevalent the "sighing" motive becomes in the highest string part. Notice, too, that much of the power of this melodic gesture derives from its context within a series of suspensions.

Let’s listen to the aria again to “Dido’s Lament,” this time following the score.

(Dido & Aeneas, Chandos Records, Ltd., 1981)

Phrase Structure

Let’s listen once more to “Dido’s Lament,” this time specifically to identify the phrases and cadences associated with the aria. Let’s go ahead and agree that there are cadences—points of relative repose—at the end of the following text phrases:

When I am laid, am laid in earth,

may my wrongs create no trouble, in thy breast.

When I am laid, am laid in earth,

may my wrongs create no trouble, in thy breast.

Remember me, Remember me, But ah! Forget my fate,

Remember me, but ah! Forget my fate!

Remember me, Remember me, But ah! Forget my fate,

Remember me, but ah! Forget my fate!

All of these phrases end with either a half cadence or an authentic cadence. And for each of these eight cadences—as it is in all tonal music—the bass “tells the tale.”

(Dido & Aeneas, Chandos Records, Ltd., 1981)
